= Something is brewing in Catalonia

Catalonia finds itself at a political and economic crossroads. Gripped by the wider Eurozone financial crisis, the region is burdened by deep austerity cuts and growing fiscal deficit. Tensions are also mounting with the Spanish government after the heavy cuts to the charter of autonomy by both the Congreso and the Constitutional Court.

President <span style='color: #002782;'>Artur Mas</span> is under heavy pressure from multiple fronts. His government has enacted unpopular austerity that have seen little effect in reducing the Generalitat's deficit nor in stimulating the economy. The renewed dissatisfaction with the Catalan-Spanish relations is also forcing his hand in assuming more pro-sovereignty stances. Now he's betting on a reform of the system of finances, hoping to kill to birds with one stone: reducing public deficit by having greater control over taxation, which would also be an expansion on the current autonomy status.

